INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c968f1c9-dc7c-4970-9043-ed0002ee92eb',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$TensorFlow Model Evaluation — Metrics, Confusion Matrices, and Cross-Validation$escape$,
  $escape$Choosing the right evaluation metric in TensorFlow depends on task type. For binary classification, use `tf.keras.metrics.AUC`, `Precision`, and `Recall` — accuracy alone is misleading on imbalanced datasets. For multiclass, `SparseCategoricalAccuracy` handles integer labels directly without one-hot encoding. For regression, `MeanAbsoluteError` and `RootMeanSquaredError` are built-in and composable.

Confusion matrices aren't native to Keras metrics but integrate cleanly via `tensorflow_model_analysis` or scikit-learn after extracting predictions with `model.predict()`. Use `tf.math.confusion_matrix(labels, predictions)` for a pure-TF tensor result you can log to TensorBoard.

Cross-validation isn't built into Keras, but you can wrap any `tf.keras.Model` with `scikeras.wrappers.KerasClassifier` to use `sklearn.model_selection.StratifiedKFold`. For large datasets, prefer manual fold loops using `tf.data.Dataset.shard()` to keep the pipeline GPU-efficient. Always reset model weights between folds with `model.set_weights(initial_weights)` to prevent state leakage.$escape$,
  $escape$import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
import numpy as np

model = tf.keras.Sequential([tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid', input_shape=(20,))])
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.AUC(name='auc'), tf.keras.metrics.Precision(), tf.keras.metrics.Recall()])

initial_weights = model.get_weights()
kf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

for fold, (train_idx, val_idx) in enumerate(kf.split(X, y)):
    model.set_weights(initial_weights)  # reset between folds
    model.fit(X[train_idx], y[train_idx], epochs=10, verbose=0)
    results = model.evaluate(X[val_idx], y[val_idx], verbose=0)
    print(f"Fold {fold+1} — AUC: {results[1]:.4f}, Precision: {results[2]:.4f}, Recall: {results[3]:.4f}")

cm = tf.math.confusion_matrix(y_true, tf.round(model.predict(X_test)))
print(cm)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
